{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478751"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:15:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:15:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18807"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18807"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.05,0.34,0.05,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11540"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102024"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11540"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18807"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84474"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"582"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"3475"},{"type":"tags","id":"4067"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35496"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43948"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102024"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of progressive abdominal distension. His parent reports decreased appetite but no vomiting or diarrhoea. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended with a fluid thrill and shifting dullness. There are dilated superficial veins on the anterior abdominal wall. His liver edge is palpable 3 cm below the costal margin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal: Haemoglobin 115 g/L (115-145), White cell count 6.5 x 10^9/L (4.5-13.5), Platelets 140 x 10^9/L (150-400), Albumin 32 g/L (35-50), Total bilirubin 25 \u03bcmol/L (3-20), ALT 45 U/L (10-35), AST 50 U/L (10-40).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Urine microscopy","Computed tomography scan","Echocardiogram","Diagnostic paracentesis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with ascites and clinical features suggestive of portal hypertension, including dilated abdominal wall veins and hepatomegaly. The mild thrombocytopenia, hypoalbuminaemia and deranged liver function tests support underlying liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic paracentesis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation as it will help determine the cause of ascites. The serum-ascites albumin gradient (SAAG) can differentiate between portal hypertensive and non-portal hypertensive causes. Additionally, cell count, protein, and culture of the ascitic fluid can help identify infection or other causes such as tuberculosis or malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the most helpful initial investigation as there are no respiratory symptoms or signs suggesting pleural effusion or pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEchocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there were features suggesting cardiac failure, such as raised jugular venous pressure, peripheral oedema, or abnormal heart sounds, which are not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography scan\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful later to evaluate liver structure and portal vessels, but it is not the most appropriate next investigation before performing diagnostic paracentesis. If any imaging investigation was going to be performed at this stage, it would be ultrasonography.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine microscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if nephrotic syndrome was suspected, but the presence of hepatomegaly and dilated abdominal wall veins makes portal hypertension more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPortal hypertension is the most common cause of ascites in children, often due to chronic liver disease. Other causes include nephrotic syndrome, tuberculosis, and malignancy. The pattern of presentation and examination findings help guide the initial diagnostic approach.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Portal hypertension is the most common cause of ascites in children","Serum-ascites albumin gradient (SAAG) \u003E11 g/L suggests portal hypertension as the cause of ascites","Diagnostic paracentesis should be performed in all new cases of ascites to guide management"],"references":["Bavdekar A, Thakur N. Ascites in Children. Indian J Pediatr. 2016 Nov;83(11):1334-1340. doi: 10.1007/s12098-016-2168-1. Epub 2016 Jun 9. PMID: 27278239."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84474"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18807"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84474","links":{"